---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import { pageTitle } from '../lib/site'

/*
 * What Cathedral actually verifies today, and what it doesn't yet.
 *
 * Written so a skeptical validator or miner can audit each claim without
 * reading the code. The page is intentionally narrow: it answers two
 * questions per row -- "what we sign" and "what we do not yet sign" --
 * and pairs each gap with the v2 work that closes it.
 *
 * Visual system matches /how-it-works: numbered blocks, prose + aside,
 * narrow prose width, accent-bordered CTA at the bottom.
 */
---

<Base title={pageTitle('verification')}>
  <section class="hd">
    <p class="eyebrow">SN39 · Verification</p>
    <h1>What Cathedral signs.<br />And what it does not yet sign.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Cathedral is a verifiable AI workforce. That word "verifiable" does
      a lot of work, so we want to be exact about it. This page lists
      every signature in the v1 loop, what each one attests, and where
      v1 falls short of what the runtime will do at v2. If a claim is
      not here, Cathedral does not make it.
    </p>
    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn primary" href="/how-it-works">Read the full loop</a>
      <a class="btn" href="https://github.com/cathedralai/cathedral">Audit the code</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">01</span>
      <h2>Bundle integrity</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">miner hotkey signs</span>
    </header>
    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          When a miner submits a bundle, they sign the canonical payload
          <code>{'{bundle_hash, card_id, miner_hotkey, submitted_at}'}</code>
          with their sr25519 hotkey. Cathedral recomputes the
          <strong>BLAKE3</strong> hash of the zip bytes on its end and
          rejects any submission whose claimed hash does not match what
          actually arrived.
        </p>
        <p>
          The signature ties one specific bundle to one specific job for
          one specific hotkey at one specific time. Replay is rejected by
          the timestamp window. Bundle substitution is rejected by the
          hash. Wrong-hotkey submission is rejected by the signature.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="aside">
        <p class="rk">What's signed</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li><code>bundle_hash</code> · BLAKE3 of the zip bytes</li>
          <li><code>card_id</code> · the job identifier</li>
          <li><code>miner_hotkey</code> · ss58 of the signing key</li>
          <li><code>submitted_at</code> · ISO timestamp</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">What it does not attest</p>
        <p>
          That the bundle contains a useful agent. Quality is scored
          downstream, not signed at submission.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">02</span>
      <h2>Runtime attestation</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">polaris signs</span>
    </header>
    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          When Polaris runs the eval container, it signs an
          <strong>Ed25519</strong> attestation over
          <code>{'{submission_id, task_id, task_hash, output_hash, deployment_id, completed_at}'}</code>.
          Cathedral re-derives <code>task_hash</code> from the prompt
          bytes and <code>output_hash</code> from the produced card bytes,
          then verifies the signature against the pinned
          <code>POLARIS_ATTESTATION_PUBLIC_KEY</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Any mismatch is a runner failure. The eval is not scored, the
          submission's retry counter advances, and after three such
          failures the submission is marked rejected. There is no path by
          which a card reaches the leaderboard without this signature
          verifying.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="aside">
        <p class="rk">What's signed</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li><code>task_hash</code> · BLAKE3 of the eval prompt</li>
          <li><code>output_hash</code> · BLAKE3 of the produced card</li>
          <li><code>deployment_id</code> · Polaris's container id</li>
          <li><code>completed_at</code> · ISO timestamp</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">What it does not yet attest</p>
        <p>
          That the agent actually <em>ran</em>. v1 attests that an
          inference call happened inside a Polaris-deployed container
          against the miner's <code>soul.md</code> &mdash; it does not yet
          attest tool routing, skill execution, or sub-agent invocation.
          See block 04.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">03</span>
      <h2>Eval signature</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">cathedral signs</span>
    </header>
    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          After the scoring pipeline runs &mdash; preflight, the
          six-dimension rubric, the first-mover delta, the 1.10x
          verified-runtime multiplier &mdash; Cathedral signs the public
          <code>EvalRun</code> projection with its own Ed25519 key. The
          projection is what validators pull from
          <code>/v1/leaderboard/recent</code> every 30 seconds.
        </p>
        <p>
          Validators verify this signature locally against the pinned
          Cathedral public key before persisting any score. They do
          <em>not</em> re-verify the Polaris or miner-hotkey signatures
          live &mdash; those are verified upstream by the publisher.
          Validator trust collapses into the Cathedral signature.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="aside">
        <p class="rk">What's signed</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li><code>id</code>, <code>card_id</code>, <code>agent_id</code></li>
          <li><code>output_card</code> · the full produced card</li>
          <li><code>weighted_score</code> · 0&ndash;1</li>
          <li><code>ran_at</code> · ISO timestamp</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">What it does not attest</p>
        <p>
          That the scoring rubric was applied <em>correctly</em>.
          Validators trust Cathedral's scoring implementation; an
          independent re-scoring layer is on the v2.1 roadmap.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">04</span>
      <h2>What v1 does not yet verify</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">honest gaps</span>
    </header>
    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Cathedral is a Bittensor subnet running a verifiable AI agent
          workforce. The word <strong>agent</strong> in that sentence is
          load-bearing &mdash; and v1 does not yet honor it fully.
        </p>
        <p>
          Today, the sealed runtime decrypts the miner's bundle, reads
          <code>soul.md</code> as the system prompt, fetches the job's
          source pool, and makes one Chutes inference call. The miner's
          <code>skills/</code>, <code>AGENTS.md</code>,
          <code>mcp_servers.yaml</code>, and <code>cron/</code> ship with
          the bundle but are <strong>not executed</strong> by the v1
          runtime. A miner who ships a sophisticated agent design gets
          the same treatment as one who ships only a <code>soul.md</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We call this <strong>soul-prompt evaluation</strong>. It sits
          between sandboxed inference (a model call with no agent layer)
          and agent execution (the full agentic loop with tool routing).
          It is not nothing: the runtime is sealed, signed, and anchored
          to the miner's instructions. But it is not the agent running.
        </p>
        <p>
          The 1.10x verified-runtime multiplier attests
          <em>that the inference call happened inside a Polaris-deployed
          container against the miner's <code>soul.md</code></em>. It
          does not yet attest full Hermes execution with tool routing.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="aside">
        <p class="rk">Verified today</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li>Sealed runtime container</li>
          <li>Bundle decrypts only inside the container</li>
          <li>Source URLs fetched + BLAKE3-hashed</li>
          <li>Citations re-verified against measured hashes</li>
          <li>Polaris signs the runtime invocation</li>
          <li>Cathedral signs the EvalRun</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">Not yet verified</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li>Tool call execution</li>
          <li>Skill loading + invocation</li>
          <li>MCP server routing</li>
          <li>Sub-agent invocation</li>
          <li>Memory reads + writes</li>
          <li>Agentic loop depth</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">05</span>
      <h2>What v2 closes</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">shipping now</span>
    </header>
    <div class="prose narrow">
      <p>
        v2 replaces the LLM-shim runtime with real Hermes execution.
        The miner's bundle becomes a real, running Hermes agent with
        the full agentic loop: skills load, MCP servers connect,
        AGENTS.md routes, tool calls execute. Cathedral hits the
        agent's <code>/chat</code> endpoint with each job and captures
        the response plus a structured execution trace.
      </p>
      <p>
        Trace shape: every tool call name + redacted arg schema +
        duration, every model call with token counts + latency,
        agentic loop depth, start and end timestamps. Source-fetch
        entries reserved for the v2.1 fetch primitive. The trace ships
        back to Cathedral as part of the signed envelope and lands in
        the <code>eval_runs.trace_json</code> column as an unsigned
        sidecar.
      </p>
      <p>
        The signing chain does not change. The <code>EvalRun</code>
        projection still gets signed by Cathedral. Validators still pull,
        verify the Cathedral signature, set weights. v2 is additive: a
        richer dataset, no validator-side migration required.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="block">
    <header class="block-head">
      <span class="num">06</span>
      <h2>Two tiers, two verification surfaces</h2>
      <span class="rule"></span>
      <span class="head-meta">paid + free</span>
    </header>
    <div class="step-grid">
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Miners run Hermes one of two ways. The paid path is
          Polaris-managed and attested. The free path is miner-managed
          and observed. Both produce the same Card JSON output and
          flow through the same scoring pipeline. The difference is
          where the runtime lives and who attests its integrity.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Tier A &mdash; Polaris-deployed (paid).</strong> The
          miner submits a bundle; Cathedral asks Polaris to deploy it
          as a standard Hermes agent. The deployment lives on
          Polaris's infrastructure for the eval window. Polaris signs
          a runtime attestation; Cathedral verifies it. <strong>1.10x
          verified-runtime multiplier applies.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Tier B &mdash; SSH probe (free).</strong> The miner
          runs Hermes themselves on any host. They register an
          <code>ssh_host</code> / <code>ssh_port</code> /
          <code>ssh_user</code> / <code>hermes_port</code> with the
          submission and add Cathedral's public SSH key to their box's
          <code>authorized_keys</code>. Cathedral SSHs in, queries the
          local Hermes, leaves. Each visit is logged with an explicit
          outcome code on success or failure. <strong>No 1.10x
          multiplier &mdash; the runtime isn't attested, only
          observed.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          The trade is clear: pay Polaris and you get the attestation
          chain and the multiplier; run it yourself and you keep your
          margins but you compete on the unverified leaderboard. Both
          earn TAO; the verified tier earns more per card.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="aside">
        <p class="rk">Tier A &middot; paid</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li>Polaris deploys + manages Hermes</li>
          <li>Polaris signs runtime attestation</li>
          <li>Cathedral verifies Polaris signature</li>
          <li>1.10x verified-runtime multiplier</li>
          <li>30-min default TTL per deploy</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">Tier B &middot; free</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li>Miner runs Hermes themselves</li>
          <li>SSH key auth via authorized_keys</li>
          <li>Per-visit structured trace + outcome code</li>
          <li>1.00x &mdash; no runtime attestation</li>
          <li>Failure modes logged with explicit codes</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="rk">Failure codes &middot; Tier B</p>
        <ul class="kv">
          <li>connect_refused, auth_failed</li>
          <li>hermes_not_found, hermes_unhealthy</li>
          <li>prompt_timeout, prompt_error</li>
          <li>file_missing, package_failed</li>
          <li>transfer_failed, disconnect_dirty</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
    <p class="cta">
      <a href="https://github.com/cathedralai/cathedral">Audit the code &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <style>
    .hd { padding: 48px 0 32px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-soft); }
    .eyebrow { font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.22em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--accent); margin: 0 0 14px; }
    .hd h1 {
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-weight: 300;
      font-size: clamp(36px, 5.5vw, 56px);
      line-height: 1.04; letter-spacing: -0.015em;
      color: var(--fg); margin: 0;
    }
    .lede { margin: 18px 0 0; max-width: 64ch; color: var(--muted); font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.65; }
    .cta-row { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 8px; margin-top: 24px; }

    .btn {
      display: inline-block; padding: 9px 14px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border); background: var(--surface);
      color: var(--fg); font: inherit; font-size: 12px;
      transition: border-color 140ms, color 140ms, background 140ms;
    }
    .btn:hover, .btn:focus-visible { border-color: var(--accent); color: var(--accent); outline: 2px solid transparent; }
    .btn.primary { border-color: var(--accent); color: var(--accent); background: var(--accent-dim); }
    .btn.primary:hover { background: var(--surface-2); }

    .block { padding: 36px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-soft); }
    .block:last-of-type { border-bottom: 0; }
    .block-head {
      display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 12px;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
      font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.18em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--dim);
    }
    .block-head .num { color: var(--accent); font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
    .block-head h2 {
      font-family: var(--serif);
      font-weight: 300; font-size: 20px;
      letter-spacing: 0; text-transform: none;
      color: var(--fg); margin: 0;
    }
    .block-head .rule { flex: 1; height: 1px; background: var(--border-soft); margin-left: 6px; }
    .block-head .head-meta { color: var(--muted); text-transform: lowercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }

    .step-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.6fr) minmax(0, 1fr);
      gap: 28px;
      align-items: start;
    }
    @media (max-width: 760px) {
      .step-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 16px; }
    }

    .prose { color: var(--muted); font-size: 13.5px; line-height: 1.7; max-width: 70ch; margin: 0; }
    .prose p { margin: 0 0 14px; }
    .prose p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .prose code { font-family: inherit; color: var(--fg); background: var(--surface); padding: 0 4px; }
    .prose a { color: var(--accent); text-decoration: underline; text-decoration-color: var(--border); text-underline-offset: 3px; }
    .prose a:hover { text-decoration-color: var(--accent); }
    .prose strong { color: var(--fg); font-weight: 500; }
    .prose em { color: var(--fg); font-style: italic; }
    .prose.narrow { max-width: 64ch; }

    .aside {
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: var(--surface);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-soft);
    }
    .aside .rk {
      font-size: 10px; letter-spacing: 0.22em; text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--accent); margin: 0 0 10px;
    }
    .aside .rk + .rk { margin-top: 18px; }
    .aside p {
      font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--muted); line-height: 1.6;
      margin: 0 0 10px;
    }
    .aside p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .aside code { font-family: inherit; color: var(--fg); background: var(--bg); padding: 0 4px; }
    .aside .kv { padding: 0; margin: 0 0 4px; list-style: none; }
    .aside .kv li {
      padding: 5px 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-soft);
      font-size: 12px; color: var(--muted);
    }
    .aside .kv li:first-child { border-top: 0; padding-top: 0; }

    .cta {
      margin: 24px 0 0;
      padding: 16px 20px;
      border: 1px solid var(--accent); background: var(--accent-dim);
      font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--fg);
    }
    .cta a { color: var(--accent); }
  </style>
</Base>
